bsorption","Increased red blood cell destruction","Chronic microscopic haematuria"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn chronic kidney disease, \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased erythropoietin (EPO) production\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism causing anaemia. The kidneys produce approximately 90% of erythropoietin in response to tissue hypoxia. As kidney function declines, erythropoietin production falls, leading to reduced red blood cell production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased hepcidin production\u003C/strong\u003E does occur and contributes to functional iron deficiency, this is a secondary mechanism. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced vitamin B12 absorption\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant factor in chronic kidney disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased red blood cell destruction\u003C/strong\u003E may occur but is not the primary mechanism. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic microscopic haematuria\u003C/strong\u003E rarely causes significant blood loss and is not a major contributor to anaemia in chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic kidney disease causes anaemia primarily through decreased erythropoietin production","Erythropoietin is primarily produced by the kidneys in response to hypoxia","Hepcidin levels increase in chronic kidney disease, leading to reduced iron availability"],"references":["Portol\u00e9s J, Mart\u00edn L, Broseta JJ, Cases A. Anemia in Chronic Kidney Disease: From Pathophysiology and Current Treatments, to Future Agents. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Mar 26;8:642296. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.642296. PMID: 33842503; PMCID: PMC8032930.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B.